<bibRefCitation author="Bigot, J. M. F." box="[1118,1243,1234,1258]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" pagination="61 - 88" refId="ref124612" refString="Bigot, J. M. F. (1883) Dipteres nouveaux oupeuconnus. 20 &quot; partie, XXXI, Genres Volucella (Geoffr., Hist, des Insectes, 1764) et Phalachromyia (Rondani, Esame d. var. spec. d'Insetti Ditteri Brasiliani, Torino, 1848); 21 e partie, XXXII, Syrphidi (2 e partie); 22 e partie, XXXII, Syrphidi (2 e partie). Especesnouvelles, no. I; Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France, Series 6, 3, 61 - 88 + 221 - 258 + 315 - 356." type="journal article" year="1883">Bigot, 1883</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
(green circles) in Chile.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="97.[151,1437,1340,1799]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,432,1340,1366]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">World distribution.</emphasis>
Originally from southern 
<collectingCountry box="[728,805,1340,1366]" name="United States of America" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">U.S.A.</collectingCountry>
to northern 
<collectingCountry box="[944,1055,1340,1366]" name="Argentina" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Argentina</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1111,1175,1340,1366]" name="Chile" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Chile</collectingCountry>
. It has been introduced to Afrotropical (
<collectingCountry box="[331,472,1376,1403]" name="Madagascar" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
), Oriental and Oceania regions.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="97.[151,1437,1340,1799]" box="[199,1096,1412,1439]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,448,1412,1438]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Chilean distribution.</emphasis>
Only recorded from 
<collectingRegion box="[683,970,1412,1439]" country="Chile" name="Arica y Parinacota" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Arica y Parinacota region</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation box="[985,1084,1412,1438]" captionStart="FIGURE 147" captionStartId="99.[151,250,1178,1202]" captionTargetBox="[185,1349,191,1123]" captionTargetId="figure-17@99.[164,1423,181,1154]" captionTargetPageId="99" captionText="FIGURE 147. Distribution map of Copestylum gibbera (Schiner, 1868) (yellow circles); Copestylum pseudotachina (Hull, 1936) (blue circles); Copestyllum scutellata (Macquart, 1842) (red circles); Copestylum yura (Curran, 1930) (black circles); Copestylum willinki (Fluke, 1951) (green circles); Ornidia obesa (Fabricius, 1775) (pink circles) in Chile." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4693588" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4693588/files/figure.png" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Fig. 147</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="97.[151,1437,1340,1799]" box="[199,918,1448,1475]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,412,1448,1474]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Altitudinal range.</emphasis>
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3080454895" box="[419,914,1448,1475]" elevation="4" location="Highland" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Highland">
<collectingRegion box="[419,523,1448,1474]" country="United Kingdom" name="Highland" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Highland</collectingRegion>
ecosystems (
<quantity box="[672,850,1448,1475]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.075" metricValueMax="4.5" metricValueMin="3.65" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" unit="m" value="4.075" valueMax="4.5" valueMin="3.65">
<elevation box="[672,850,1448,1475]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.075" metricValueMax="4.5" metricValueMin="3.65" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" unit="m" value="4.075" valueMax="4.5" valueMin="3.65">3,650–4,500 m</elevation>
</quantity>
.a.s.l.)
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="97" pageNumber="98" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="97.[151,1437,1340,1799]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,419,1484,1510]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Biology and notes.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[426,588,1484,1510]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Ornidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obesa">
<emphasis box="[426,588,1484,1510]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Ornidia obesa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widely distributed from the 
<collectingCountry box="[937,991,1484,1510]" name="United States of America" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">USA</collectingCountry>
to northern 
<collectingCountry box="[1130,1191,1484,1510]" name="Chile" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Chile</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1245,1360,1484,1510]" name="Argentina" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Argentina</collectingCountry>
. In the Neotropical region, the species is associated with several disturbed ecosystems due to its synanthropic behavior. It is important to notice that this species is usually distributed in low and middle elevations except for 
<collectingCountry box="[1277,1338,1556,1582]" name="Chile" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Chile</collectingCountry>
where it seems to be restricted to highlands. Larvae are saprophagous of decaying plant species, fruits and non-woody plants. In addition, this species could be associated with animal waste and dung (
<bibRefCitation author="Rotheray, G. E. &amp; Hancock, E. G. &amp; Marcos-Garcia, M. A. &amp; Zumbado, M." box="[994,1241,1628,1655]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" pagination="419 - 427" refId="ref138020" refString="Rotheray, G. E., Hancock, E. G., Marcos-Garcia, M. A. &amp; Zumbado, M. (2006) Early stages and breeding sites of three species of Neotropical Ornidia (Diptera, Syrphidae). Studia Dipterologica, 12, 419 - 427." type="journal article" year="2006">
Rotheray 
<emphasis box="[1107,1165,1628,1654]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">et al.</emphasis>
, 2006
</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry box="[1293,1356,1628,1654]" name="Chile" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Chile</collectingCountry>
, adults have been recorded visiting flowers of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Rich.) E. E. Schill. &amp; Panero" authorityName="E. E. Schill. &amp; Panero" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName="Rich." box="[588,1167,1664,1691]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Aldama" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="helianthoides">
<emphasis box="[588,833,1664,1690]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Aldama helianthoides</emphasis>
(Rich.) E.E. Schill. &amp; Panero
</taxonomicName>
(Rodrigo Barahona-Segovia pers. obs.)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="97.[151,1437,1340,1799]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,445,1736,1762]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Conservation status.</emphasis>
LC; AOO = 
<quantity box="[595,653,1736,1762]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" unit="km" value="8.0">8 km</quantity>
<superScript attach="left" box="[653,661,1736,1750]" fontSize="6" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">2</superScript>
and two localities (or subpopulations). This species is widely distributed in the New World.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
